<div id="review_1024965697" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1024965697" />
    <a title="Abby" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6843326-abby"><img alt="Abby" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1342372957p2/6843326.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1024965697?book_show_action=true">Aug 12, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Abby" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Abby" href="/user/show/6843326-abby">Abby</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781602860742" href="/book/show/6325666-the-gift-of-rain">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6843326-abby?shelf=2014">2014</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1024965697" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13167164012880130944">Sometimes a good story, reasonably well told, is enough. And this is a hell of a good story in a beautifully evoked and exotic setting -- Malaya in 1939 and through the war. Philip Arminius Khoo-Hutton, a lonely sixteen-year-old whose Chinese mother died when he was a child, feels estranged from his prominent British colonial family and forms an ever-closer and more powerful connection with Hayato Endo, a Japanese diplomat and aikido master. Endo-san becomes Philip&apos;s sensei, both martial arts tr</span>
  <span id="freeText13167164012880130944" style="display:none">Sometimes a good story, reasonably well told, is enough. And this is a hell of a good story in a beautifully evoked and exotic setting -- Malaya in 1939 and through the war. Philip Arminius Khoo-Hutton, a lonely sixteen-year-old whose Chinese mother died when he was a child, feels estranged from his prominent British colonial family and forms an ever-closer and more powerful connection with Hayato Endo, a Japanese diplomat and aikido master. Endo-san becomes Philip's sensei, both martial arts trainer and spiritual guide. When war comes, the British abandon Malaya and Philip realizes he has been unwittingly complicit in the Japanese invasion and occupation. Conflicting loyalties to his family, his country and his mentor tear at Philip and drive both questionable and courageous decisions as his world falls apart.<br /><br />Tan Twan Eng's Malaya is a lush, seductive place, physically beautiful and rich with cultural cross-currents. His lyrical descriptive prose is often lovely. But people and their interactions are less deftly drawn, the dialog stilted and bordering on parody. (In one passage, all hungrily thrusting swords and Philip opening himself up to Endo-san, their relationship seemed to be going to a new place, never to be hinted at again.) As in many historical novels, the history is often clumsily presented. And there are too many schlocky fictional devices: wondering-if-I'd-ever-see-him-agains, b-movie action scenes, predestination from previous lives, hokey ancient wisdom.<br /><br />This is an ambitious saga -- a coming-of-age story and an exploration of collaboration and resistance in wartime -- maybe too ambitious for a debut novel. It's far from great literature but it's competent storytelling, a novel you can sink into, savor the richness of the sights and smells, and maybe even learn from.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13167164012880130944" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


