<div id="review_3540120377" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3540120377" />
    <a title="Carol Orange" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/9264803-carol-orange"><img alt="Carol Orange" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1599700063p2/9264803.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3540120377?book_show_action=true">Sep 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Carol Orange" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Carol Orange" href="/user/show/9264803-carol-orange">Carol Orange</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3540120377" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11626002902928088299">The Gift of Rain by Tan Twan Eng<br/><br/>In 1939 the lush Malayan island of Panang was part of the waning British Empire. The island’s residents included Chinese, Phillipinos, Indians, English businessmen, a sprinkling of Japanese and of course Malaysians. <br/><br/>Phillip Hutton, the protagonist, is the youngest son in a British family of successful businessman, Noel Hutton. Phillip’s mother, a beautiful Chinese woman died when he was young. Phillip was her only child. His two older brothers and sister were from</span>
  <span id="freeText11626002902928088299" style="display:none">The Gift of Rain by Tan Twan Eng<br /><br />In 1939 the lush Malayan island of Panang was part of the waning British Empire. The island’s residents included Chinese, Phillipinos, Indians, English businessmen, a sprinkling of Japanese and of course Malaysians. <br /><br />Phillip Hutton, the protagonist, is the youngest son in a British family of successful businessman, Noel Hutton. Phillip’s mother, a beautiful Chinese woman died when he was young. Phillip was her only child. His two older brothers and sister were from Noel Hutton’s previous marriage to a British woman who died in childbirth. <br /><br />Early in 1939, when his family is in England for 6 months, Phillip who is now sixteen, takes a boat trip to a small island about a mile out from his family home. His family owns the island, but his father has rented the house on it to a Japanese man named Endo-san. Endo-san and Phillip connect and the story dramatically changes as the Japanese master of aikijutsu becomes Phillip’s martial arts teacher as well as his friend.<br /><br />Tan Twan Eng’s saga about the Malay peninsula is deeply moving as all the native worlds collide after the Japanese invade. Phillip, in his wish to protect his family, becomes an unwillingly traitor to his people while he secretly works to save as many lives as possible. <br /><br />This complex debut novel is written beautifully. It reveals a world that I knew nothing about. My heart was broken by all the tragic deaths, but Phillip survives and lives to tell the tale.<br /><br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11626002902928088299" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


