    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_53893569" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/53893569" />
    <a title="Chrissie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie"><img alt="Chrissie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1321799585p2/632247.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/53893569?book_show_action=true">Apr 24, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chrissie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chrissie" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie">Chrissie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=malaysia">malaysia</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=japan">japan</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=kirkus">kirkus</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=hf">hf</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=text-checked">text-checked</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer53893569" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4140258425594540823">NO SPOILERS<br/><br/>This book is clearly a mixed bag for me. It is in short about Philip, the son of a British father and Chinese mother, and his relationship with his Japanese sensei. It takes place in Malaya during WW2 when the Japanese occupied the country, sending the British running for their lives. The friendship between Philip and his older Japanese teacher, his sensei, begins before the occupation, before Philip ever became aware of the conflict of interests that will arise between the Malayan in</span>
  <span id="freeText4140258425594540823" style="display:none">NO SPOILERS<br /><br />This book is clearly a mixed bag for me. It is in short about Philip, the son of a British father and Chinese mother, and his relationship with his Japanese sensei. It takes place in Malaya during WW2 when the Japanese occupied the country, sending the British running for their lives. The friendship between Philip and his older Japanese teacher, his sensei, begins before the occupation, before Philip ever became aware of the conflict of interests that will arise between the Malayan inhabitants (Indians, Chinese and English living on the island of Penang) and the Japanese. The teaching begins with aikido training, but soon progresses to include an entire philosphy of life. Since Chinese, Japanese and Malayan people are represented in the community, the book is able to in depth illuminate the customs, traditions and philophies of the different groups. This is extremely well done. The history of the Japanese invasion is well explained. The reader isn't told, but experiences what this might have been like. The plot is moving and keeps you turning the page to find out what will happen next. <br /><br />I felt that the writing drew me in. I felt I was there. The ways of the people are cleverly interwoven into the storytelling. You are not given a text book rendition. I will site a few examples. When Philip first meets his grandfather, who had denied his existence since he opposed his daughter's marriage to a British man, proper etiquette had to be strictly adhered to:<br /><br />"On my first visit I had to sit across the table from him as etiquette decreed, but he had said, very irritably, 'No, no. Come and sit next to me.' And so after that I always sat by his side without being asked ...Then I would pour tea for him. The first time I had done so he had watched me fill the cup, rapping the second joints of the fore and middle fingers of his right hand softly on the table. It happened whenever I served him and eventually I asked him the significance of it." <br /><br />"'That is how we thank the person serving us,' he replied. 'All Chinese people are familiar with it.'" (page 243)<br /><br />And then the grandfather goes on to explain the origin of this custom. I found this fascinating. <br /><br />This is simply one example, but the book is chock full with such descriptions. Philip learn Japanese traditions from his sensei and Chinese ones from his grandfather. <br /><br />I like the philosophical questions that are raised. The Japanese sensei, Endo-san, is Philip's self-chosen teacher. As a teacher, the philosophical threads fit well into the narrative, but such discussions are not restricted to only these two. <br /><br />"That is what growing old consists of, mostly. One starts giving away items and belonings until only the memories are left. In the end, what else do we really require?"<br /><br />"I examined her words carefully, and the answer came slowly but without any equivocation. 'Someone to share the memories with,' I said finally surprising myself." (page 411)<br /><br />Or listen to the following:<br /><br />"The older one gets, the more one wishes to simplify one's life." (page 243)<br /><br />THAT is certainly true. <br /><br />Then there is a discussion between Philip and his half-sister Isabel about their mother. <br /><br />"She (Isabel) rolled her glass of wine between her hands, like a potter giving shape to his creation. 'Perhaps you're right. Memory is a tricky thing. When I said I have no memory of my mother, I meant I don't remember her here,' she touched her forehead, 'and yet-' her hands returned to shaping her glass. <br /><br />"'And yet you feel her here, I said resting my hand on the spot above my heart."<br /><br />"I stopped her moving hands and held them tight, feeling the harness of the wineglass beneath, almost on the point of cracking. 'That's not memory, Isabel,' I said. 'That's love.'" <br /><br />"She blinked her eyes again, and ran a finger across them, hiding her tears. We had revealed more about ourselves in those few moments than we had in recent years. Was this part of the process of growing up, that we finally noticed the people closest to us in a different, clearer light?" (pages 211-212)<br /><br />Thoughts kept my head churning. <br /><br />I must also note that the description of particular places was occasionally breathtaking. If it was raining, you felt the rain. The author drew little pictures in my mind that were utterly beautiful. Here is one example, when Philip, as an older man many years after the war, is in a little rowboat at night with a friend:<br /><br />"I dipped the oars into the water and slowed our progress. 'Close your eyes', I said. I switched off the flashlight and studied the movement of the clouds. The wind was pushing them across the weak moon, gradually filtering out its light from the sky, turning the night completely dark."<br /><br />"When we had drifted to the right place further down the river, I whispered softly, 'Now - open your eyes.'"<br /><br />"She drew in her breath. A light layer of mist rose up from the surface of the river and, in the trees, shining as though stars had fallen to earth, tens of thousands of fireflies were sending out their silent mating signals. We were caught in a frenzy of fragmented light."<br /><br />I don't know about you, but I think that is beautiful. Draw your own picture!<br /><br />The author's descriptive abilities are also used to describe savage Japanese torture procedures. <br /><br />So why only three stars? The sensei, Philips's father, grandfather and other relatives all believe that fate plays an all-important role in our lives. This is also a recurring theme of the entire book. This and other concepts of rebirth are a bit too metaphysical for my tastes. I simply cannot accept the idea proposed that our lives are ruled by fate. I do not believe we come back again as another identity. I cannot believe in the cyclical reappearnace of people. I do realize that this way of thinking IS strong in the East, but for me such beliefs only weakened the believability of the characters. The author failed to make this philosophy something I might understand. My inability to understand the way Philip and his sensei reason makes their choices seem absurd. I just don't find their actions believable. For me the portrayal of the two main characters falls flat. How can I feel empathy for cardboard, two-dimensional characters who have no pulse in their veins? Here the author has failed me. I think this book is overrated. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4140258425594540823" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

