<div id="review_4016807280" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4016807280" />
    <a title="Blair" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/272909-blair"><img alt="Blair" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1641384776p2/272909.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4016807280?book_show_action=true">Jul 13, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Blair" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Blair" href="/user/show/272909-blair">Blair</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9781905802517" href="/book/show/23444633-the-gift-of-rain">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/272909-blair?shelf=2000s-release">2000s-release</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/272909-blair?shelf=first-novels">first-novels</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/272909-blair?shelf=read-on-kindle">read-on-kindle</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/272909-blair?shelf=past-and-present">past-and-present</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4016807280" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11287916573842256389">(3.5) When I decided to read this book, I was looking for something specific – a long, involving, atmospheric historical novel set somewhere outside the UK/US. I’ve owned the ebook since 2012, having bought it after reading the author’s Booker-shortlisted <em>
  <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12031532.The_Garden_of_Evening_Mists' title='The Garden of Evening Mists by Tan Twan Eng' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Garden of Evening Mists</a>
</em> (although I must have forgotten to shelve it on Goodreads at the time). I don’t remember much about the plot of <em>Evening Mists,</em> but I remember something of how it felt to read: contemplative, soothing and immersiv</span>
  <span id="freeText11287916573842256389" style="display:none">(3.5) When I decided to read this book, I was looking for something specific – a long, involving, atmospheric historical novel set somewhere outside the UK/US. I’ve owned the ebook since 2012, having bought it after reading the author’s Booker-shortlisted <em>
  <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12031532.The_Garden_of_Evening_Mists" title="The Garden of Evening Mists by Tan Twan Eng" rel="nofollow noopener">The Garden of Evening Mists</a>
</em> (although I must have forgotten to shelve it on Goodreads at the time). I don’t remember much about the plot of <em>Evening Mists,</em> but I remember something of how it felt to read: contemplative, soothing and immersive. I was in the mood for more of that.<br /><br /><em>The Gift of Rain</em> is told as the recollections of a man named Philip Hutton. Now entering old age, he still lives in his childhood home on Penang Island, Malaysia, and has been largely solitary for most of his life. When an unexpected visitor arrives, he’s prompted to reassess his past – particularly the parts of it that involved Hayato Endo, an enigmatic Japanese diplomat who taught the young Philip the art of Aikido. The plot goes on to focus (in great depth) on the Japanese invasion of Malaya in 1941 and subsequent occupation, during which Philip is torn between two branches of his family (his British father and siblings, and the Chinese relatives of his late mother) and his loyalty to his Japanese tutor.<br /><br />The story is interesting, illuminating and well told. All my problems with it come from that unfortunate conundrum of a book simply not doing what you <em>want</em> it to do. In the end, the lengthy descriptions of various battles and conspiracies tried my patience, and I felt frustrated by a strange coyness in the narrative regarding the true nature of the relationship between Philip and Endo-san. I was looking for a meandering historical tale, and that is indeed what this is; I just ended up wanting more of the central characters than I was given.<br /><br /><a href="https://tinyletter.com/learnthisphrase" rel="nofollow noopener">TinyLetter</a> | <a href="https://linktr.ee/learnthisphrase" rel="nofollow noopener">Linktree</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="11287916573842256389" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


