  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2167438617" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2167438617" />
    <a title="Jeanette" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11869072-jeanette"><img alt="Jeanette" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1372095557p2/11869072.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2167438617?book_show_action=true">Nov 12, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jeanette" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jeanette" href="/user/show/11869072-jeanette">Jeanette</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2167438617" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12202704777650954272">What to say!!!<br/><br/>Many post of the lyrical and exquisite balance of language, and the intense emotion of connections between Philip and his sensei. And the world of their island in Malaysia during this pre-war and WWII years. And the aftermath.<br/><br/>No plot tell here or synopsis. There&apos;s much action, it&apos;s not all poetic scenery and house parties. Book 1 is so well done that you felt that you were another set of eyes to Endo-san&apos;s island, and the lessons given there. But yet, I never lost that sense- other</span>
  <span id="freeText12202704777650954272" style="display:none">What to say!!!<br /><br />Many post of the lyrical and exquisite balance of language, and the intense emotion of connections between Philip and his sensei. And the world of their island in Malaysia during this pre-war and WWII years. And the aftermath.<br /><br />No plot tell here or synopsis. There's much action, it's not all poetic scenery and house parties. Book 1 is so well done that you felt that you were another set of eyes to Endo-san's island, and the lessons given there. But yet, I never lost that sense- others feel quite differently I see- that no 16 year old should ever be left in such material and spiritual choices with his family half a world away for 6 or more months. Let alone at that period of time when businessmen of such status and connections KNEW the lay of the land and had heard the sabers rattling for half a decade already. At least that long. No one mentions that in all of these reviews? The incredible naivete to put a child of mixed ancestry with his own servants in a place where bloodlines and family / tribal/ clan ties are 75% of all living and function! Especially for Philip's father- to be that dismissive of reality? <br /><br />Regardless, it is extremely long and the love stories expressed are coupled with attachment, mentoring of extreme physical and emotional connections, and the sense of "not a fit" or "different" or "not belonging" always at some point within the mix. Not only for Philip either. <br /><br />Book 2 and onwards until the much later day episodes with the two survivors that loved Endo-san is probably in the top 10 for all the saddest tales that I've ever read. And the entire great length is in some way an attempt to achieve the state of ambivalence for Endo-san and his choices and decisions for the "audience", the reader. And as such also Philip's which are so tied to his prime teacher and role model.<br /><br />And it seems to have been successful if I read the reviews and reactions here correctly. Most feel ambivalent. I never did. I feel more strongly than Isobel about the roles played. The past lives' roles, the family connection roles, the present day roles, and even the souls connections for the future. Brutal is brutal. Torture is torture. Evil of such whole piece belief system equals the products of its acts. Not only its words.<br /><br />But in this length and with so much substantiation of affect, this lonely boy and the life he experienced from 16 to 24! There was always some valid reason- some "good". And a predestined path to be walked. <br /><br />I'm with Philip's mother. This beautifully pictured cosmic scale? It is just a twisted and rusted metal contraption with humans consistently throwing in their own heavy thumbs on either side of the balance. <br /><br />Because I've read 4 or 5 books set in multi-language Malaysia this year- I have to add that the "Hill" houses and so much else of that changing world then and quite decades afterwards- that all was 5 star. Tan Twan Eng CAN write. I especially like how he posits all things in such gentle method wording. That's a gift. And it's never quite direct in language either, always building up or coming at you from "the sides".<br /><br />This is an extremely brutal and ultimately visceral account of Japanese occupation. Don't forget that if you decide to read this book. It is certainly not for everyone. And it was well done, but overlong. I enjoyed about 3/4th of it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12202704777650954272" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review2167438617">
